1 : GitHub push (Source Stage): The workflow begins when a developer pushes a code change to a specified branch in a GitHub 
repository. A webhook is typically configured to detect this change and trigger the pipeline.
2 : Jenkins builds (Continuous Integration): Triggered by the GitHub push, the Jenkins automation server pulls the latest 
code from the repository. It then executes a build process, which may include compiling the code, running unit tests, 
and performing other checks to ensure code quality.
3 : Docker packages (Build and Delivery): Assuming the build and tests are successful, Jenkins creates a Docker image of
the application. The Docker image is a standardized package that includes the application code and all its dependencies,
ensuring it runs consistently across different environments. The image is then pushed to a container registry, like 
Docker Hub or Amazon ECR.
4 : Deploy on AWS EC2 (Continuous Deployment): Following the successful packaging, Jenkins deploys the new Docker image
to a specified Amazon EC2 instance. The deployment process typically involves pulling the new image from the container 
registry, stopping the old container, and starting a new container with the updated image.
5 : Users can access app (Post-Deployment): With the new container running on the EC2 instance, the application is live 
and accessible to end-users. The automation ensures that new code changes are rolled out quickly and reliably. 


