⚙️ Step-by-Step Flow
1️⃣ Developer Builds the Application

You write your Java (Spring Boot) code and build a .jar file using Maven or Gradle.

2️⃣ Dockerization

You create a Dockerfile and build a Docker image of your app:

docker build -t myapp .


Now this image contains:

Your code

Java runtime

All dependencies

So it can run anywhere.

3️⃣ Push Docker Image to Registry

You push that image to a Docker Registry (like Docker Hub, AWS ECR, GitLab, etc.):

docker push myrepo/myapp:latest


This is like storing your packaged app in a central location.

4️⃣ CI/CD Pipeline (Jenkins, GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, etc.)

Now comes the CI/CD part:

CI (Continuous Integration): Automatically builds, tests, and creates the Docker image when you push code to Git.

CD (Continuous Deployment): Automatically pulls the latest Docker image and deploys it to the server (or Kubernetes).

So, CI/CD automates:
✅ Build
✅ Test
✅ Dockerize
✅ Deploy

5️⃣ Deployment (in Production or Cloud)

The CI/CD tool pulls your Docker image and runs it as a container on:

A server (like EC2)

A Kubernetes cluster

A Docker Swarm environment

Your app is now live 🎯

